# Steps for Hypothesis Testing
# 1) Formulate our Hypothesis (H0: no change vs. Ha: change)
# 2) Calculate the Standard Error (sigma/sqrt(n), s/sqrt(n), sqrt(p(1-p)/n))
# 3) Calculate the Test Statistic ( (observed - hypothesized)/SE )
# 4) Draw ourselves a picture and then calculate the p-value (Probability value is more extreme then test statistic given null is true)
# 5) Compare the p-value to the significance level (0.05)
#   -> p-value < 0.05 we reject the Null (getting this sample is very rare if the null is true)
-> p-value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null (getting this sample is not unusual given the null)
# Average height of people is 70 inches with a standard error of 5 inches
# We sample 50 people and find the sample mean height to be 71 inches tall. We want to see if the population mean height is different then 70  inches
# H0: mean height = 70 vs. Ha: mean height != 70
SE <- 5/sqrt(50)
SE
test_stat <- (71 - 70)/SE
test_stat
pnorm(-1.414)*2
(1-pnorm(1.414)) * 2
# Since the p-value (0.1574) is greater than 0.05 so we fail to reject the null
# We do not have evidence to say the mean height is not 70 inches tall
# H0: mean height = 70 vs. Ha: mean height != 70
SE <- 5/sqrt(50)
test_stat <- (72 - 70)/SE
test_stat
(1-pnorm(2.8284)) * 2
# Since the p-value (0.0047) is less than 0.05 so we reject the null
# We have evidence to say the mean height is not 70 inches tall
# Because it is really rare to get a sample mean of 72 given the population is 70
